"1313":"1313","1224":"1224","about  1220 (20-29)":"about 1220","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","1220":"1220","1184":"1184","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Hooley House, Coulsdon, Surrey, England":"Hooley House, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Hooley House, Surrey, England":"Hooley House, Surrey, England","All Saints’ Parish Church, Sanderstead, Surrey, England":"Sanderstead, Surrey, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Piers","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Regular medieval vernacular form of   Peter   (from the Old French nominative case, as against the oblique <i>Pier</i>, modern <i>Pierre</i>). In the form <i>Pierce</i> it survived into the 18th century, although in part this may be a transferred use of the surname derived from the medieval given name. <i>Piers</i> was revived in the mid-20th century, perhaps partly under the influence of  William Langland's  great rambling medieval poem Piers Plowman (  1367–86 ), in which the character of Piers symbolizes the virtues of hard work, honesty, and fairness."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter Piers De Wyckhurst Sr. was born about 1195, in Hooley House, Surrey, England, his father, William de Wyckhurst, was 36 and his mother, Alice Fosse, was 40. He died about 1220, in Surrey, England, at the age of 27, and was buried in Sanderstead, Surrey, England."},"et":{"about 1195–about  1220 (20-29)":"umbes 1195–umbes 1220","1195–1220":"1195–1220","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","1220–1313":"1220–1313","1224–1278":"1224–1278","1160–1200":"1160–1200","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","about 1195":"umbes 1195","1215":"1215","1313":"1313","1224":"1224","about  1220 (20-29)":"umbes 1220","1278":"1278","1200":